# validate-upstream-mojo-fix-hostile-home-matrix — History

## v2.0.0 (2026-05-25)

**Changed by:** Session validating modular/modular#6413 (AVX-512 mis-emission on masked-AVX-512 CPUs) on a different ProjectOdyssey Mojo bump branch. Confirmed 47+ green required-check runs end-to-end before opening the demolition wave.

**Verification:** verified-ci

### What changed

- **Generalized scope**: skill no longer covers only the `getAcceleratorArchOrEmpty()` / `std::filesystem::status` family (modular#6412). It now documents a reusable **4-gate validation protocol** that applies to ANY upstream Mojo runtime / codegen fix landing in a pinned-nightly bump.
- **Hostile-`$HOME` matrix retained as Gate 1 Example A** (worked example for filesystem-error class bugs). Quick Reference still includes the 8-shape recipe verbatim — backward-compatible for anyone landing here from a #6412 search.
- **Added Gate 1 Example B**: `mojo build --print-effective-target` codegen check for compiler-driver / target-resolution bugs (Example: AVX-512 feature-flag mis-emission on masked-AVX-512 hosts, modular#6413). Compares pre-fix vs post-fix driver output on the same host as the cheapest possible signal.
- **Added Gate 2**: Dispatch the project's existing `repro-<issue#>` workflow ≥10× consecutively on the bump branch. Includes the load-bearing caveat that pre-fix infrastructure (coredump capture composite actions, gdb wrappers) often breaks for reasons unrelated to the fix — read the actual Mojo invocation logs, not the workflow's pass/fail summary.
- **Added Gate 3**: Run any existing soak workflow at full iteration count (same caveat as Gate 2 re: broken infra).
- **Added Gate 4**: ≥8 consecutive green runs across ALL required checks on the bump branch — the strongest signal because it exercises real project workload, not synthetic reproducers. Often catches stdlib API regressions that ride along with the bump (e.g., removed `UnsafePointer._unsafe_null=()` constructor) that must be fixed on the same branch before demolition begins.
- **Added "Strategic positioning of the validation branch"** section: keep the validation PR open as a historical canary even after demolition starts; close only after the first demolition wave merges.
- **Updated frontmatter**: bumped `version` 1.0.0 → 2.0.0, `date` to 2026-05-25, `verification` from `verified-local` to `verified-ci`, expanded `description` to cover the protocol broadly, added `history` field, added tags (`codegen-flags`, `avx512`, `four-gate-protocol`, `ci-canary`, `target-cpu`).
- **Added 3 new Failed Attempts rows** (8, 9, 10) covering: spending cycles fixing pre-fix infrastructure that's slated for deletion, dismissing Gate 4 stdlib API regressions as flakes, and closing the validation PR too early.

### Why

The skill at v1.0.0 was narrowly framed around a single bug (`getAcceleratorArchOrEmpty()` `std::filesystem::status` throw). When validating modular#6413 — a completely different bug class (AVX-512 feature flags emitted on a CPU that lacks AVX-512 EVEX-encoded ops, causing SIGILL at JIT execution time) — the hostile-`$HOME` matrix was useless because the bug had nothing to do with filesystem permissions. But the *structure* of the validation effort was recognizably the same as #6412: prove the fix is in the binary cheaply first (Gate 1), then escalate to CI dispatch (Gate 2), then soak (Gate 3), then full required-check matrix (Gate 4).

The right abstraction is the 4-gate framework. The hostile-`$HOME` matrix is one instantiation of Gate 1 for a specific bug class. The new codegen `--print-effective-target` check is another. Future Mojo runtime fixes will need their own Gate 1 recipes, but Gates 2/3/4 are reusable as-is.

Generalizing also surfaces the caveats nobody documented at v1.0.0: pre-fix infrastructure tends to rot once the bug is gone, and Gate 4 sometimes catches *new* problems (stdlib API churn) that arrived in the same nightly bump.

### Previous version (v1.0.0) snapshot

```yaml
---
name: validate-upstream-mojo-fix-hostile-home-matrix
description: "Validate that an upstream Mojo runtime crash fix (specifically the
  `getAcceleratorArchOrEmpty()` / `std::filesystem::status` family — modular/modular#6412
  and any successor) actually landed in your newly-bumped nightly BEFORE peeling
  back downstream Dockerfile/entrypoint workarounds. Uses a hostile-`$HOME` matrix
  (mode 000, mode 750+700, missing dir, /dev/null, unset) on a one-line `def main`
  binary. Use when: (1) you bumped the pinned Mojo version past the upstream
  fix-shipped date and want to confirm the fix landed in your build, (2) you are
  about to peel back a downstream workaround (sudoers `_ensure_writable`,
  `chmod 755 /home/$USER`, entrypoint `mkdir -p $HOME/.modular`, HOME-redirect
  fallback) and need a deterministic confirmation, (3) your container runtime is
  rootless and blocks `setpriv`/`runuser`/`sudo -u nobody`, so a true UID-mismatch
  reproducer is impossible locally and you need a permission-shape proxy instead,
  (4) an upstream Modular issue closed with 'fix in next nightly' and you want to
  verify the claim before commenting on the issue or opening a workaround-removal PR."
category: testing
date: 2026-05-13
version: "1.0.0"
user-invocable: false
verification: verified-local
tags:
  - mojo
  - modular
  - upstream-validation
  - container
  - permissions
  - filesystem-error
  - getAcceleratorArchOrEmpty
  - hostile-home
  - workaround-removal
  - rootless-podman
---
```

Body summary: 8-shape hostile-`$HOME` bash matrix targeting only modular#6412
filesystem-error class; verified-local only; 7 Failed Attempts rows covering
version-premise checks, sudoers/setpriv/runuser limitations in rootless podman,
Mojo 1.0 `fn`→`def` migration, removed `mojo test` subcommand, and PAT scoping
for `gh issue comment` on third-party repos. Full content preserved in the
v1.0.0 git history at the previous commit on main.

